\chapter{System Design}
Containing a comprehensive description of the design chosen, how it addresses the problem, and why it is designed the way it is.

\section{Introduction}

The SCALE platform (Secure Coding Learning Environment) is designed as a secure, role-aware, web-based system for practical cybersecurity education. The core design objective is to let students safely interact with intentionally vulnerable behaviours, verify remediation correctness, and receive structured feedback, without exposing the host infrastructure to untrusted code execution risk.

The implemented architecture uses a hybrid style: service decomposition at deployment level (frontend, backend API, AI service, multiple databases, sandbox image builder), with layered modular organisation inside the backend FastAPI service. This combination was selected to preserve implementation velocity while isolating high-risk operations and keeping interfaces explicit.

Chapter 3 defined 28 functional requirements (FR01--FR28) and 18 non-functional requirements (NFR01--NFR18). This chapter maps those requirements to the implemented design: architectural viewpoints, data model decisions, interfaces, implementation strategy, testing traceability, and deployment blueprint. All descriptions below are aligned with the currently implemented codebase and Docker topology.

\section{Architecture Design viewpoints}

\subsection{Context viewpoint}

The Context viewpoint describes SCALE as a bounded system exposing security-learning services to external actors.

\textbf{Primary actors}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Student}: authenticates, uploads projects for scanning, executes challenge attacks, submits code fixes, takes quizzes, views progress analytics, and downloads pentest-style reports.
    \item \textbf{Instructor}: manages quiz content/assignments, monitors class and per-student analytics, communicates with students, and can reset student progress for integrity management.
    \item \textbf{Administrator}: manages users and roles, approves instructors, reviews security logs/statistics, and supervises overall platform operation.
    \item \textbf{Docker Engine}: technical actor used by backend sandbox execution to build and run ephemeral containers for fix validation.
    \item \textbf{AI Service}: externalised assistant endpoint consumed by backend for AI-powered quiz preview and mentor workflows.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{System boundary services}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Authentication and role-based authorization.
    \item Challenge attack/fix workflows and hint/state tracking.
    \item Project upload, extraction, static vulnerability scanning, and risk scoring.
    \item Learning analytics, progress calculations, and dashboards.
    \item Messaging and security event logging.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Design concerns addressed}
\begin{itemize}
    \item NFR01 sandbox isolation and NFR02 role-based access control.
    \item FR03--FR06 deterministic fix validation.
    \item FR22--FR23 security observability and governance.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Composition viewpoint}\label{ss-comp}

SCALE is decomposed into collaborating runtime subsystems:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Frontend subsystem} (React + Vite + TypeScript + Tailwind): role-aware SPA, challenge UI, scanner views, dashboards, messaging screens.
    \item \textbf{Backend API subsystem} (FastAPI monolith): auth, business logic, scanner orchestration, challenge endpoints, stats, messaging, reporting.
    \item \textbf{AI subsystem} (separate FastAPI container): AI preview/generation endpoint consumed via HTTP.
    \item \textbf{Sandbox subsystem} (Docker SDK via backend): ephemeral per-submission image build and test execution.
    \item \textbf{Database subsystem}: three MySQL instances:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item main\_db: core platform data.
        \item challenge\_db\_sqli: SQL injection lab dataset.
        \item challenge\_db\_csrf: CSRF lab dataset.
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

Inter-subsystem communication occurs through REST APIs and SQL connections; sandbox orchestration uses Docker socket integration from backend.

