\subsection{Patterns use viewpoint}

To satisfy committee guidance, only patterns demonstrably present in implementation are included:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Layered architecture (applied)}: presentation (React SPA), application (FastAPI routers), domain logic (security/scanner/learning modules), infrastructure (MySQL, Docker, ReportLab, OpenAI client).
    \item \textbf{Dependency Injection (applied)}: FastAPI \texttt{Depends()} usage for DB sessions, authentication, and role checks.
    \item \textbf{Broker-style API orchestration (applied)}: backend acts as a broker between frontend and downstream services (AI service, sandbox runtime, scanner/report generators).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Important note}: classical GoF patterns not represented in the implemented class structure are intentionally omitted.

\subsubsection{Design Rationale}

These patterns were selected to maximize auditability and maintainability while preserving secure boundaries around untrusted operations. Dependency injection centralizes authorization and data access constraints. Layering reduces coupling between UI concerns and execution/security infrastructure.

\subsection{Algorithm viewpoint}

